ynamic reports and the coverage of certain tests. I wonder about the role of bootstrap classes and how they might influence this. \\n\\nAh, if the `class$` field is only called once, could that cause issues in metadata generation? It might not be initializing correctly, especially since previous tests occur before dynamic coverage begins. There’s a lot to unravel here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining Gradle and Reflection Issues**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether Gradle's separate discovery or classpath scan invokes the test. I wonder if dynamic-access coverage relies on static JVMTI traces and filters out the class$. \\n\\nTo test this, I could add a call to `class$` using JUnit’s `ReflectionSupport.invokeMethod`. It seems like this would cover the synthetic methods involved. Since the user wants the active class, I can use `org.junit.platform.commons.support.ReflectionSupport`, which requires a Method object. However, direct reflection in tests isn't advisable unless necessary, and there might be some complications with accessing package-private methods. It's tricky!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Private Lookup in Classpath**\\n\\nI’m considering whether `privateLookupIn` can access methods from an unnamed module if the caller has full privileges, even if they're from a different package. It seems that calling `privateLookupIn(target, MethodHandles.lookup())` can grant private access if the module is open. Since the unnamed module is, finding static \\\"class$\\\" this way would allow us to bypass java.lang.reflect APIs. This method call could effectively work and bypass some of the restrictions I’ve been thinking about.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java visibility**\\n\\nI’m checking whether the Java compiler recognizes class$ in the binary. It might not if it's synthetic, and since `javap` didn’t mark it, it could be an issue. The method name with `$` is legal, and it seems that the source in the same package can use it directly without reflection. Still, I’m concerned because the test helper is in a library package. I’m also considering whether I can create a helper in the correct package but realize there are visibility constraints.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering static field access**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether I can set a static field to null using the public API. It seems that's not possible. The most reliable method would be to access it directly in the same package, but that violates the package rule. However, it feels somewhat less concerning. The user's rules from the developer must be followed, but I'm wondering if using a test class that's outside could be a workaround. Still, the helper might fall under the library package, so I can't do that. Maybe a direct method handle would be acceptable since it fits in with the public API's requirements?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering exception handling**\\n\\nIt seems like I may have made things worse if the agent didn’t account for the exception path. I need to remove the throwing test or move it after the no-exception scenario. The original `returnNull` was supposed to cover things but may not have worked because it came after `findsFields`, leading the first absence to return null without considering exceptions. Perhaps I should cover this with the no-exception path and reset the static null before proceeding, without making any direct adjustments?\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_HUgbZYzbL7OBEziuJu9jsPbB|fc_0ae0813c41bf96820169fcd154f528819eae211dcff8ab1131", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/plexus/plexus-utils/1.0-alpha-2/src/test/java/plexus/plexus_utils/ReflectionUtilsTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    @Test\n    @Order(1)\n    void triggersObjectClassLookupWhenSearchReachesTopOfHierarchy() {\n        assertThatThrownBy(() -> ReflectionUtils.getFieldByNameIncludingSuperclasses(\"missingValue\", Object.class))\n        